WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.730
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:23.230 --> 00:00:26.010
&gt;&gt; Hi, I'm Mark Horowitz from
the Music Division of the Library

00:00:26.010 --> 00:00:31.750
of Congress and I'm here with the
master musician Jason Robert Brown

00:00:31.750 --> 00:00:34.510
and we're here mostly
to discuss music.

00:00:34.510 --> 00:00:39.250
I don't know if you, we called
this sort of oral history

00:00:39.250 --> 00:00:41.960 position:56%
but it's going to be fairly focused.

00:00:41.960 --> 00:00:47.000
&gt;&gt; Is there something else I
would be qualified to discuss?

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:50.830
&gt;&gt; I wanted to start, there is an
aphorism attributed to Ned Rorem

00:00:50.830 --> 00:00:54.080
and it goes something like
amateurs talk about meanings

00:00:54.080 --> 00:00:56.580
and professionals talk about means.

00:00:56.580 --> 00:01:01.600
What I want to know first is
the physical how you work.

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:05.620
Do you work at a piano, do you
have a computer next to you,

00:01:05.620 --> 00:01:10.510
do you record as you're
playing, do you make notes?

00:01:10.510 --> 00:01:12.520
&gt;&gt; I feel like I'm
sort of in the middle

00:01:12.520 --> 00:01:16.160
of changing how all of that works.

00:01:16.160 --> 00:01:18.950
It used to be that I would sit at
the piano and sort of bang things

00:01:18.950 --> 00:01:22.630
out and you know, I would know,

00:01:22.630 --> 00:01:24.810
before I sat down at the
piano I would have a title,

00:01:24.810 --> 00:01:29.210
usually I'd have a precede of what
the song was going to be in my head

00:01:29.210 --> 00:01:32.760
which I'd encapsulated in a couple
of words and so I would sing

00:01:32.760 --> 00:01:35.930
that title and I'd have
an instinctive sense

00:01:35.930 --> 00:01:42.390
of what is the tonality, is
it a major key, minor key,

00:01:42.390 --> 00:01:45.130
and what is the style of
it, is it sort of jazzy,

00:01:45.130 --> 00:01:47.060
is it sort of rocky, is
it sort of classical?

00:01:47.060 --> 00:01:51.670
And you know, the basic parameters
around that so before I sit

00:01:51.670 --> 00:01:53.970
down at the piano I've already
made a couple of decisions

00:01:53.970 --> 00:01:57.790 position:56%
but then the piano is going to start
influencing a bunch of the decisions

00:01:57.790 --> 00:01:59.560
that I make from there on out.

00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:05.970 position:56%
And so, I'll start singing along and
gradually sort of carve out a shape

00:02:05.970 --> 00:02:10.010
of a melody or at the very
least a harmonic progression

00:02:10.010 --> 00:02:11.840
and some rhythmic ideas in terms

00:02:11.840 --> 00:02:15.140
of where the melody is
going to live within that.

00:02:15.140 --> 00:02:17.650
So, I'll do all of
that and sort of come

00:02:17.650 --> 00:02:19.990
up with a basic structure
for how the song works.

00:02:19.990 --> 00:02:23.230
I usually will stop at the
bridge and just leave the bridge

00:02:23.230 --> 00:02:26.810
for a minute but just get those
first chunks done you know,

00:02:26.810 --> 00:02:28.910
what's the verse structure,
what's the chorus structure

00:02:28.910 --> 00:02:33.220
and am I using a conventional
structure or am I going

00:02:33.220 --> 00:02:35.510
to ski the powder and sort
of see where it leads me.

00:02:35.510 --> 00:02:39.400 position:56%
And you know, I'll sort of start
making those decisions as I carve it

00:02:39.400 --> 00:02:42.710
out and then gradually
fitting words to it and some

00:02:42.710 --> 00:02:44.010
of the words will have come

00:02:44.010 --> 00:02:46.390
up as I've started just singing
things randomly at the piano.

00:02:46.390 --> 00:02:49.160
Some words will sort of find
their way into my subconsciousness

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:51.540
because I mean, I know again
what the character is thinking

00:02:51.540 --> 00:02:54.990
so there's certain phrases that
I'll start just sort of improvising

00:02:54.990 --> 00:02:59.140
and those might suddenly I'll go,
oh and that actually fits nicely

00:02:59.140 --> 00:03:01.320
over this and then that rhymes
nicely with that and then oh,

00:03:01.320 --> 00:03:02.810
I see where I want to go.

00:03:02.810 --> 00:03:08.730 position:56%
So all of that stuff is going on and
it's all sort of very free formed

00:03:08.730 --> 00:03:12.720
but it's directed you
know, it's not random.

00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:16.880
I always know sort of what
the end result should be,

00:03:16.880 --> 00:03:20.670
it just takes me a lot of
synthesizing to get there.

00:03:20.670 --> 00:03:23.620
And then, once I've got
a basic verse structure

00:03:23.620 --> 00:03:27.240 position:56%
and a basic chorus structure, I will
usually go away and just chip away

00:03:27.240 --> 00:03:30.990
at lyrics for a while and just
sort of get all that to line up

00:03:30.990 --> 00:03:35.760
and there are oftentimes where I
never get back to the piano again

00:03:35.760 --> 00:03:38.000
until the first time I'm
showing the song to somebody,

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:41.230
which may even include a
bridge that I've written

00:03:41.230 --> 00:03:42.530
and I just know what
it is in my head

00:03:42.530 --> 00:03:45.340
but I've never actually put my
fingers on the keys to do it,

00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:47.770
but you know they'll be someone
coming over to hear the song

00:03:47.770 --> 00:03:49.730
and I'll be like oh, and I'll
just pull it out of the printer

00:03:49.730 --> 00:03:51.030
and I'll say all right here it was.

00:03:51.030 --> 00:03:55.200
And I try to write lyrics by hand
because I sort of think better

00:03:55.200 --> 00:03:59.370
through my pen then I do
when I'm typing but again,

00:03:59.370 --> 00:04:00.670
it depends on the deadline.

00:04:00.670 --> 00:04:04.830
I can sort of do it however but
I don't notate score usually

00:04:04.830 --> 00:04:08.940
until the very end of
the process because much

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:12.680
of what I'm doing is
chordally based as so as long

00:04:12.680 --> 00:04:17.040
as I know what the general harmonic
progression is I'm not so caught

00:04:17.040 --> 00:04:21.100
up in the specifics
of the accompaniment

00:04:21.100 --> 00:04:24.050
or I know what they are so
specifically that I don't have

00:04:24.050 --> 00:04:25.350
to write them down for a while,

00:04:25.350 --> 00:04:28.230
but I actually prefer the
organic letting it come

00:04:28.230 --> 00:04:34.260
out of my hands first, let my
hands get used to what the feel

00:04:34.260 --> 00:04:38.550
of the song is and then I
will start really shaping it

00:04:38.550 --> 00:04:41.980
into the notated accompaniment.

00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:44.480
But when I say that I'm in
the middle of changing that,

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:46.990 position:56%
when I did Bridges of Madison County
I wrote most of that on guitar,

00:04:46.990 --> 00:04:49.160
which is not an instrument
that I really play but I wanted

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:53.400
to have tonalities that were not
what I usually hit with my fingers

00:04:53.400 --> 00:04:56.820
and so because I was writing on
an instrument that I didn't know,

00:04:56.820 --> 00:04:59.860
I couldn't just call up a bunch
of things that I knew how to do.

00:04:59.860 --> 00:05:03.630 position:56%
That was much more of an exploratory
process where I would just pick

00:05:03.630 --> 00:05:07.150
up the guitar and sit with it and
just sort of make noises on it

00:05:07.150 --> 00:05:12.580
and as I would come up with
shapes, accompaniment figures,

00:05:12.580 --> 00:05:17.100
structural ideas, I would say does
this feel like this character,

00:05:17.100 --> 00:05:20.460
does that feel like what I
want this moment to feel like?

00:05:20.460 --> 00:05:23.540 position:56%
And as I got a little more fluent on
the instrument, and I never got good

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:26.900
at it but as I got more fluent
on it, I eventually was able

00:05:26.900 --> 00:05:30.280 position:56%
to anticipate some things and was
able to make certain decisions ahead

00:05:30.280 --> 00:05:33.390
of time but I'd say the first three
or four things I wrote for Bridges

00:05:33.390 --> 00:05:36.310
of Madison County on the
guitar were very sort of like,

00:05:36.310 --> 00:05:40.720
I don't know what's going to happen
and I liked that sort of looseness

00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:43.110
and craziness, but within
that looseness then the rest

00:05:43.110 --> 00:05:45.120
of the process was very similar.

00:05:45.120 --> 00:05:48.930
Once I would sort of see a
light at the end of the tunnel,

00:05:48.930 --> 00:05:51.980
then I knew how to sort
of push towards it.

00:05:51.980 --> 00:05:57.160
But lately, I've also been doing a
lot more of recording stuff as I'm

00:05:57.160 --> 00:06:00.220 position:56%
in the middle of writing it and then
just letting it marinate for a while

00:06:00.220 --> 00:06:02.640
or sometimes I'll layer
recordings on top of each other

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:07.120
and I'll use the garage bands
on my Mac and sort of let

00:06:07.120 --> 00:06:10.350
that be a template for things.

00:06:10.350 --> 00:06:12.800
There was one project that I
had to write very, very quickly

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:15.020
and it all had to be
very idiomatic music,

00:06:15.020 --> 00:06:16.890
it all needed to be really
rock music and I found

00:06:16.890 --> 00:06:21.620 position:56%
that I just used the drum loops from
garage band which are very generic

00:06:21.620 --> 00:06:26.210
and I just used those, and I didn't
use any of the harmonic loops

00:06:26.210 --> 00:06:28.160
that they have on there
because that felt like cheating

00:06:28.160 --> 00:06:31.710
but I used the drum loops and just
played along with them and I felt

00:06:31.710 --> 00:06:35.250 position:56%
like oh, now I feel like I'm in that
band and that's doing that thing

00:06:35.250 --> 00:06:37.680
for me so I did that, but
I don't think I would do

00:06:37.680 --> 00:06:40.630
that for a more legit project.

00:06:40.630 --> 00:06:45.200
This was for a commercial
thing that I was doing.

00:06:45.200 --> 00:06:48.690
&gt;&gt; You've talked a lot about the
importance of structure in songs

00:06:48.690 --> 00:06:53.680
so when you have this initial
idea, do you have a sense

00:06:53.680 --> 00:06:59.410
that this is going to be, the A
section will be about this topic,

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:02.470
then it will go here
and the bridge will go

00:07:02.470 --> 00:07:04.370
that direction or it's not that-

00:07:04.370 --> 00:07:06.740
&gt;&gt; I sort of, I feel like
there are a lot of songs

00:07:06.740 --> 00:07:09.730
where I may have outlined
that in advance.

00:07:09.730 --> 00:07:12.490
There are certainly, I
think the vast majority

00:07:12.490 --> 00:07:17.310
of my songs you can diagram
them that way after the fact.

00:07:17.310 --> 00:07:19.480
&gt;&gt; But not going into it?

00:07:19.480 --> 00:07:21.340
&gt;&gt; Well, I think going
in it's very clear

00:07:21.340 --> 00:07:23.510
to me what I'm doing
with the first verse.

00:07:23.510 --> 00:07:26.880
I always know where the song is
starting and then I will need

00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:28.570
to do something else
for the second verse

00:07:28.570 --> 00:07:30.660
because I have a real
philosophy about the way

00:07:30.660 --> 00:07:35.210
that theater songs have to function
and what justifies repetition

00:07:35.210 --> 00:07:37.940
because to me, it feels
like if the music is going

00:07:37.940 --> 00:07:40.660
to repeat itself them dramatically
you can't be repeating yourself.

00:07:40.660 --> 00:07:44.460
The lyrics have to be taking you
someplace else and when I teach,

00:07:44.460 --> 00:07:50.540
I often have a think I talk about
how if you're going to be trying

00:07:50.540 --> 00:07:53.650
to convince somebody of
something you might say it to them

00:07:53.650 --> 00:07:55.320
and if they didn't get it
you might say it again,

00:07:55.320 --> 00:07:57.440
but you're not just going to say
it a third time without trying

00:07:57.440 --> 00:08:00.030
to find some other way around
it, some way to elaborate into it

00:08:00.030 --> 00:08:01.330
and so I always think of that

00:08:01.330 --> 00:08:03.550
as the B section is bridge
and then the final A.

00:08:03.550 --> 00:08:05.970
&gt;&gt; But dramatically, you
know where you're starting.

00:08:05.970 --> 00:08:08.290
Do you know where you want
that character to end?

00:08:08.290 --> 00:08:10.490
&gt;&gt; If you're lucky you do.

00:08:10.490 --> 00:08:15.970
If I'm honest with
who the character is,

00:08:15.970 --> 00:08:19.540
then I should know before I start
the song what I hope for it to end

00:08:19.540 --> 00:08:23.560
with but I say that and I
have been surprised often

00:08:23.560 --> 00:08:27.340
by where the characters take me
over the course of writing the song

00:08:27.340 --> 00:08:30.200
and sometimes it's something
as simple as a rhyme is going

00:08:30.200 --> 00:08:33.280
to lead me over here and
because the rhyme led me there,

00:08:33.280 --> 00:08:35.810
suddenly the character
feels something

00:08:35.810 --> 00:08:38.320
and learns something that's
not untrue to the character

00:08:38.320 --> 00:08:40.880
but it may not have been what
I intended the song to say.

00:08:40.880 --> 00:08:44.170
But having said it all of
a sudden, it lifts the song

00:08:44.170 --> 00:08:45.590
and likewise I can have that

00:08:45.590 --> 00:08:50.300
and then it sends the whole song
off the cliff and then I have

00:08:50.300 --> 00:08:52.640
to go and rescue it back.

00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:57.150
But I think in terms of the
sort of [inaudible] structure

00:08:57.150 --> 00:09:01.980
over everything, there is always a
general sense that you're going to,

00:09:01.980 --> 00:09:04.900
at some point over here if this is
the whole piece then at some point

00:09:04.900 --> 00:09:07.410
over here there's going to be the
kind of ultimatum of the song,

00:09:07.410 --> 00:09:08.990
there's going to be
some real turning point

00:09:08.990 --> 00:09:12.840 position:56%
about what the piece is and then the
resolution which is either positive

00:09:12.840 --> 00:09:17.200
or negative or even stasis,
however things resolve from here.

00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:19.430
But all of the thing
that gets you up to

00:09:19.430 --> 00:09:24.830
that point is really asking the
questions and finding other ways

00:09:24.830 --> 00:09:27.480 position:56%
to ask the questions and I feel
like that's what the song always is.

00:09:27.480 --> 00:09:30.610
The song is a series of
demands and questions trying

00:09:30.610 --> 00:09:32.170
to lead up to a decision.

00:09:32.170 --> 00:09:35.860
I think there are some songs
of mine that are very clear how

00:09:35.860 --> 00:09:38.340
that all works, I was thinking
You Don't Know This Man is a song

00:09:38.340 --> 00:09:40.390
that you know exactly
sort of what it's doing

00:09:40.390 --> 00:09:43.450
because dramatically it's meant
to be sort of the first A,

00:09:43.450 --> 00:09:44.930
she won't look at him
when she's talking

00:09:44.930 --> 00:09:46.650
and then the second A
she looks directly at him

00:09:46.650 --> 00:09:49.470
and then the bridge you know,
she really pins it right on him

00:09:49.470 --> 00:09:52.980
and the finals statement, the final
A she shuts him down and I feel

00:09:52.980 --> 00:09:56.120
like you really see
sort of what that is

00:09:56.120 --> 00:10:00.050
because she's actually just talking
to herself over the course of that.

00:10:00.050 --> 00:10:02.640
But then you know, something like
The Schmuel Song, which is seven

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:05.600
and a half minutes long, there is
still the exact same [inaudible]

00:10:05.600 --> 00:10:09.210
structure to it but what it takes
in order to get there you know,

00:10:09.210 --> 00:10:11.890
I remember while writing
it I don't know

00:10:11.890 --> 00:10:13.980
when I'm going to get out of this.

00:10:13.980 --> 00:10:16.510
You know, it was just sort of
taking me all of these places

00:10:16.510 --> 00:10:20.260
and I was enjoying the ride and I
thought the song was benefitting

00:10:20.260 --> 00:10:24.040
from the ride but I really thought
this song might be 20 minutes long,

00:10:24.040 --> 00:10:27.740
it might be two minutes long,
I don't know because the path

00:10:27.740 --> 00:10:29.520
over to here was so windy

00:10:29.520 --> 00:10:31.930 position:56%
that I just couldn't tell how long
it was going to take me to get there

00:10:31.930 --> 00:10:35.140 position:56%
and then when it did finally wrap up
it was like oh I see it, I see it,

00:10:35.140 --> 00:10:38.180
I see it, I get it and then I
could sort of put a bow on it.

00:10:38.180 --> 00:10:41.790
But you know, so I think those are
the kind of two extremes you know,

00:10:41.790 --> 00:10:46.950
structurally of what my
songs are but you know,

00:10:46.950 --> 00:10:49.880
I do always have a general sense
of what the song is supposed

00:10:49.880 --> 00:10:52.030
to accomplish and then
there are tweaks

00:10:52.030 --> 00:10:53.520
and specifics that I think get all-

00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:56.770
&gt;&gt; And there's surprises
to you as it goes along.

00:10:56.770 --> 00:10:59.760
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I mean to me it's
the most fun when there are.

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:01.910
You know, if it's exactly
what you thought it was going

00:11:01.910 --> 00:11:04.220
to be then really you're just
being a secretary to your brain,

00:11:04.220 --> 00:11:07.290
which is not as much fun.

00:11:07.290 --> 00:11:09.990
You know, what there really
is, is there's this thing

00:11:09.990 --> 00:11:12.660
where your brain does,
it makes some leap

00:11:12.660 --> 00:11:15.920 position:56%
that you didn't know it was going to
make and that's why you're a writer.

00:11:15.920 --> 00:11:17.220
I mean, that's why I'm a writer.

00:11:17.220 --> 00:11:19.660
It's just those moments
where you're like oh, oh,

00:11:19.660 --> 00:11:21.870
I didn't know that was coming and
I didn't know that was going to be

00:11:21.870 --> 00:11:26.050
that and that's perfect, that's
exactly what that's supposed to be

00:11:26.050 --> 00:11:28.820
and I have such a sense of pride
in those moments and such a sense

00:11:28.820 --> 00:11:30.460
of accomplishment in those moments.

00:11:30.460 --> 00:11:32.960
That's sort of what
I'm working towards.

00:11:32.960 --> 00:11:36.620
It's why I write slowly also
is I don't want to just sort

00:11:36.620 --> 00:11:38.220
of all right, I know what
this song is and I write it.

00:11:38.220 --> 00:11:40.760
I think I always could, I
think I could do that now

00:11:40.760 --> 00:11:42.430
if you said write it, I could
just go ahead and write it

00:11:42.430 --> 00:11:46.400
but the real joy is in
making all of it sort

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:52.110 position:56%
of click together exactly right in
some way that I can't see right now.

00:11:52.110 --> 00:11:55.150
&gt;&gt; Somewhere you wrote I think
in the intro to something,

00:11:55.150 --> 00:11:57.870
to the libretto for
The Last Five Years,

00:11:57.870 --> 00:12:00.940
that you remember writing
the opening number

00:12:00.940 --> 00:12:03.350
on this particular day.

00:12:03.350 --> 00:12:09.670
Is there a typical time that it
takes to write a song, a range?

00:12:09.670 --> 00:12:12.950
&gt;&gt; I think the reason I can
tell you I wrote that song

00:12:12.950 --> 00:12:16.840 position:56%
on any particular day or anything
like that is there are those moments

00:12:16.840 --> 00:12:21.570
where a song sort of
clicks, they're very powerful

00:12:21.570 --> 00:12:26.090
and so a song can take three weeks
to write but there is a moment

00:12:26.090 --> 00:12:29.520
in which the song sort
of coalesces into a thing

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:33.090
and that can be you know, when
you're two weeks in to trying

00:12:33.090 --> 00:12:34.930
to figure it out or
it can be just sort

00:12:34.930 --> 00:12:37.230
of on the first minute
that you have it.

00:12:37.230 --> 00:12:38.620
I mean, there are certainly,

00:12:38.620 --> 00:12:40.300
even recently there are
songs I've written very,

00:12:40.300 --> 00:12:42.940
very quickly that just
sort of poured out of me

00:12:42.940 --> 00:12:44.990
that were very satisfying.

00:12:44.990 --> 00:12:50.200
Actually, the last two songs
that I wrote there's a song

00:12:50.200 --> 00:12:52.970
that I'm writing for the
connector which is very,

00:12:52.970 --> 00:12:59.160
very complicated long sort of
rap, punk, crazy thing that I did

00:12:59.160 --> 00:13:01.690
and it took me the better part
of three months to write it

00:13:01.690 --> 00:13:06.760
because it was just so dense and
the information had to be parsed

00:13:06.760 --> 00:13:09.630
in exactly the right way so
the audience could hear it.

00:13:09.630 --> 00:13:12.330
And it just took me a long time to
figure out how to do all of that

00:13:12.330 --> 00:13:14.710
and then there was the song I
wrote the day after the election

00:13:14.710 --> 00:13:18.800 position:56%
which was Hope, which I wrote in I
think 18 or 19 minutes and you know,

00:13:18.800 --> 00:13:21.740
both immensely satisfying
songs to me but you know,

00:13:21.740 --> 00:13:27.440
the process by which they all
come is sort of a little crazy.

00:13:27.440 --> 00:13:32.060 position:56%
But I remember the day I finished up
the song for The Connector as well.

00:13:32.060 --> 00:13:33.360
&gt;&gt; What is The Connector?

00:13:33.360 --> 00:13:36.290
&gt;&gt; The Connector is one of the
new pieces that I'm working on.

00:13:36.290 --> 00:13:37.590
&gt;&gt; It's a show?

00:13:37.590 --> 00:13:38.930
&gt;&gt; It's a show, yes.

00:13:38.930 --> 00:13:44.470 position:56%
&gt;&gt; When you're writing a show song
versus a stand along song like Hope,

00:13:44.470 --> 00:13:48.960
is it an entirely different thing,
you're writing for your voice,

00:13:48.960 --> 00:13:51.820
not for a character in a situation?

00:13:51.820 --> 00:13:54.860
&gt;&gt; It's not an entirely different
thing but it's a different thing.

00:13:54.860 --> 00:14:00.750
Knowing that I'm going to
sing it generally means also

00:14:00.750 --> 00:14:05.700
that my band is going to play
it so there are different things

00:14:05.700 --> 00:14:09.120
that I do musically when
I'm writing for myself

00:14:09.120 --> 00:14:12.920
but without sounding pretentious
about it, there is myself

00:14:12.920 --> 00:14:14.880
as a character, there
is myself as the person

00:14:14.880 --> 00:14:17.220
on stage singing the
song which is a thing.

00:14:17.220 --> 00:14:20.060
You know, it's different than me
sitting at the dining room table.

00:14:20.060 --> 00:14:26.300
I wouldn't be singing so
there is a certain distance.

00:14:26.300 --> 00:14:31.950 position:56%
It is an intangible and unmeasurable
distance between me and that guy

00:14:31.950 --> 00:14:35.900
but there is still a
character involved in that

00:14:35.900 --> 00:14:38.250
and when I'm writing a
character for a show,

00:14:38.250 --> 00:14:42.210
then I'm definitely
inside a different person.

00:14:42.210 --> 00:14:44.740
There are even times when
I'm writing songs for shows

00:14:44.740 --> 00:14:48.790
that I know I'm going to want to
do in my act, that I know I'm going

00:14:48.790 --> 00:14:53.420
to want to do with my band and
I do approach those differently.

00:14:53.420 --> 00:14:56.190
I find that the songs I write for
the guys I tend to really think

00:14:56.190 --> 00:14:59.040
about am I going to want to sing
this whereas the songs I write

00:14:59.040 --> 00:15:03.130
for the girls I tend not to think
that because I'm not likely to

00:15:03.130 --> 00:15:06.140 position:56%
and then sometimes I'll end up with
one where like, oh I have to do this

00:15:06.140 --> 00:15:09.160
and I'll make accommodations
for that.

00:15:09.160 --> 00:15:15.860
But it is in my head and I
don't think it's a bad thing.

00:15:15.860 --> 00:15:20.150
I think there's, because musical
theater is essentially meant to be

00:15:20.150 --> 00:15:22.710
on a stage, it is meant
to be performed,

00:15:22.710 --> 00:15:25.070
being able to anticipate
the performative aspects

00:15:25.070 --> 00:15:29.960
of the material I think is part
of what makes my stuff what it is.

00:15:29.960 --> 00:15:34.620
I mean, I think part of why my
songs breathe in the particular way

00:15:34.620 --> 00:15:38.360
that they do is that I
know that I will need to,

00:15:38.360 --> 00:15:42.480
physically myself I will need
to defend them behind a piano.

00:15:42.480 --> 00:15:47.250
If I can't do it, then I can't
ask somebody else to do it.

00:15:47.250 --> 00:15:50.000
&gt;&gt; Back to the original
sort of question,

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:56.060
when you sort of completed a
song, what do you physically do?

00:15:56.060 --> 00:15:57.360
Do you write out a lead sheet?

00:15:57.360 --> 00:15:58.810
Do you write a complete-

00:15:58.810 --> 00:16:02.120
&gt;&gt; Oh no, no, no, at this point

00:16:02.120 --> 00:16:04.830
when I'm done writing
a song I'll record it

00:16:04.830 --> 00:16:08.660
and I'll do a pretty elaborate, I
mean obviously I have good fingers

00:16:08.660 --> 00:16:15.610 position:56%
so I can do a pretty elaborate piano
demo and if it needs musical means

00:16:15.610 --> 00:16:18.930
that the piano does not
accurately represent,

00:16:18.930 --> 00:16:21.510
if your imagination
would require a leap

00:16:21.510 --> 00:16:23.680
that I can't expect your
imagination to take in order

00:16:23.680 --> 00:16:26.320
to understand what the song is,
then I'll also put other things on.

00:16:26.320 --> 00:16:29.890
I'll put percussion instruments on,
or I'll put my guitar playing on,

00:16:29.890 --> 00:16:32.950
none of which is very good but
it's just to give you an idea

00:16:32.950 --> 00:16:34.570
that this is not supposed
to sound like me sitting

00:16:34.570 --> 00:16:37.390
at the piano so I'll make the demo.

00:16:37.390 --> 00:16:42.280
I have one assistant who
transcribes just the vocal line

00:16:42.280 --> 00:16:44.190
because that is really
just secretary work

00:16:44.190 --> 00:16:48.080
and so they'll just transcribe the
vocal line for me and then sort

00:16:48.080 --> 00:16:52.330
of any obvious piano figures,
anything that you can hear

00:16:52.330 --> 00:16:55.400
in the accompaniment that I
clearly do over and over again,

00:16:55.400 --> 00:16:57.680
that's something that
must be in there

00:16:57.680 --> 00:17:00.370
and then leave the rest
of the piano part blank.

00:17:00.370 --> 00:17:05.180 position:56%
And so, they'll deliver to me a
finale file which has the vocal line

00:17:05.180 --> 00:17:08.750
in it and sort of whatever of the
piano part was worth grabbing,

00:17:08.750 --> 00:17:11.890
anything that will
save me a little time.

00:17:11.890 --> 00:17:16.680 position:56%
And when the singers first get the
material in a reading in a workshop,

00:17:16.680 --> 00:17:19.440
usually that's all they get.

00:17:19.440 --> 00:17:22.080
My Music Director Tom
Murray, will often sketch

00:17:22.080 --> 00:17:25.560
in more complete accompaniments
but I deliberately keep those

00:17:25.560 --> 00:17:29.270
out of my personal files because I
don't want to get sort of seduced

00:17:29.270 --> 00:17:32.500 position:56%
by how easy it is to just use those.

00:17:32.500 --> 00:17:35.650
So Tom will sort of feather
in some fake accompaniment

00:17:35.650 --> 00:17:37.310 position:56%
so that he can play it at rehearsals

00:17:37.310 --> 00:17:40.810
or so other rehearsal pianists
can do it and then eventually,

00:17:40.810 --> 00:17:44.730
usually when it's time to
orchestrate I will first write

00:17:44.730 --> 00:17:47.910
out a more fully realized
piano part even

00:17:47.910 --> 00:17:52.050 position:56%
if that isn't what the piano part
is going to be in the orchestration.

00:17:52.050 --> 00:17:54.980
I just sort of like to reduce it
something that I can then work

00:17:54.980 --> 00:17:57.250
from on a very concrete,
because orchestration

00:17:57.250 --> 00:17:59.150
for me is still a very
concrete thing.

00:17:59.150 --> 00:18:01.210
I know there's a lot of people that
just play things and the keyboards,

00:18:01.210 --> 00:18:07.040
they work in a more abstract
way then that but for me I need

00:18:07.040 --> 00:18:10.400
to see two stabs worth
of dots and I'm like,

00:18:10.400 --> 00:18:14.310
okay now I know what I want to
do around it and I know enough

00:18:14.310 --> 00:18:19.160
to eviscerate all of the dots
but for me that's a useful guide.

00:18:19.160 --> 00:18:21.300
And again, if I have to work
really fast I don't need that,

00:18:21.300 --> 00:18:25.270
I know what I have to do but in
the ideal world I'll realize an

00:18:25.270 --> 00:18:27.830
accompaniment fairly fully
and that's the accompaniment

00:18:27.830 --> 00:18:29.210
that will get in the
vocal selections,

00:18:29.210 --> 00:18:31.160
that will get in the published
scores, that will sort of be all

00:18:31.160 --> 00:18:33.730
that and then I'll
orchestrate it from there

00:18:33.730 --> 00:18:35.040
if I'm doing the orchestration.

00:18:35.040 --> 00:18:37.510
If someone else is
doing the orchestration,

00:18:37.510 --> 00:18:40.220 position:56%
if I send it to Sebesky or if I send
it to Charlie Rosen, or if I send it

00:18:40.220 --> 00:18:43.450
to Sam Davis or anybody else
you know, then they'll usually,

00:18:43.450 --> 00:18:49.350 position:56%
Sebesky writes by hand and illegibly
so I'll get Sebesky's charts back

00:18:49.350 --> 00:18:53.410
and I'll usually have to have the
copyist do that into a finale file

00:18:53.410 --> 00:18:57.960
so that I can actually just read
what it is because it's just

00:18:57.960 --> 00:18:59.480
like your doctor's prescription,

00:18:59.480 --> 00:19:03.230
it's completely illegible
except to the copyist.

00:19:03.230 --> 00:19:05.630
And so once I get that,
then I will do a lot

00:19:05.630 --> 00:19:07.820
of corrections to anybody's charts.

00:19:07.820 --> 00:19:13.800
I fix a lot of orchestrations,
I fiddle and so I'll correct,

00:19:13.800 --> 00:19:16.570
if I get it from Charlie or from
Sam they'll send me finale files

00:19:16.570 --> 00:19:17.870
and I'll usually do
the corrections right

00:19:17.870 --> 00:19:19.860 position:56%
into finale which I know how to use.

00:19:19.860 --> 00:19:23.050
I'm not fast at it and I
don't like it very much.

00:19:23.050 --> 00:19:25.970
There's something I like about
the tactility of pencils.

00:19:25.970 --> 00:19:32.190
And so then that sort of goes off
into the world and I have a copyist

00:19:32.190 --> 00:19:34.890
in Chicago who does the
vast majority of my work

00:19:34.890 --> 00:19:38.020
and so then he'll get
all of it extracted

00:19:38.020 --> 00:19:41.940 position:56%
and then there's usually generations
upon generations upon generations

00:19:41.940 --> 00:19:45.390
of fixes and cleanups and things
like that until you get to a place

00:19:45.390 --> 00:19:47.120
where it can finally get published.

00:19:47.120 --> 00:19:51.840 position:56%
But for early shows like Songs For a
New World, those materials are still

00:19:51.840 --> 00:19:55.620
in fairly lousy shape and that is
largely because it just takes me

00:19:55.620 --> 00:20:00.040
so long to say what I
want the piano part to be.

00:20:00.040 --> 00:20:05.860 position:56%
And so everything that has to happen
thereafter goes really fast like,

00:20:05.860 --> 00:20:07.910
I'm writing a piano part and here
are the orchestrations and go

00:20:07.910 --> 00:20:10.960
and then everything is just fixes,
and fixes, and fixes, and fixes

00:20:10.960 --> 00:20:14.450
and it costs money to fix all those
things, which I don't usually have

00:20:14.450 --> 00:20:17.000
and nobody is generally
offering me so things can get

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:19.220
in pretty loosy goosy
shape for a while.

00:20:19.220 --> 00:20:22.730
I think Parade we finally
have perfectly corrected

00:20:22.730 --> 00:20:25.530 position:56%
and fixed scores for full orchestra.

00:20:25.530 --> 00:20:31.940
The show premiered in 1998, I
think I got those done in 2015.

00:20:31.940 --> 00:20:35.810
&gt;&gt; Tunick uses a phrase
the eye that hears,

00:20:35.810 --> 00:20:42.880
and as I understood him he sort
of visualizes the actual music

00:20:42.880 --> 00:20:47.740
in his head as he's working, he
sort of sees the dots in his brain.

00:20:47.740 --> 00:20:54.490 position:56%
The fact that you're so, that you're
not writing things down initially

00:20:54.490 --> 00:21:00.360
and you're a musician, what
are you holding in your brain?

00:21:00.360 --> 00:21:03.830
Are you actually seeing the
music when you're playing things?

00:21:03.830 --> 00:21:05.130
Is it-

00:21:05.130 --> 00:21:06.430
&gt;&gt; No, I mean, I have layer.

00:21:06.430 --> 00:21:09.210
I have layers that I sort of
am aware of layers of music

00:21:09.210 --> 00:21:11.650
as I'm listening to
it, I hear in layers,

00:21:11.650 --> 00:21:13.980
I sort of hear they compress
and then they expand.

00:21:13.980 --> 00:21:18.180
I mean, that would be a pretty cool
visual idea to try and explain it

00:21:18.180 --> 00:21:23.040
so I wasn't literate first, I
was an illiterate musician first.

00:21:23.040 --> 00:21:26.290
I didn't come from the
dots out, I had a very,

00:21:26.290 --> 00:21:30.630
very rudimentary you know, I
started when I was eight years old

00:21:30.630 --> 00:21:33.200
and so I had a very rudimentary,
this is what a middle C is

00:21:33.200 --> 00:21:35.570
and so I could do it
but I was just too lazy

00:21:35.570 --> 00:21:37.770
and I preferred playing things.

00:21:37.770 --> 00:21:40.670
You know there wasn't back
then any kind of school

00:21:40.670 --> 00:21:45.140
of idiomatic piano playing other
than this is how you learn how

00:21:45.140 --> 00:21:47.150
to play Liszt and this is how
you learn how to play Chopin,

00:21:47.150 --> 00:21:50.880
which wasn't very interesting to
me and so I bailed out of that

00:21:50.880 --> 00:21:54.590 position:56%
and just became sort of a player
who played whatever I wanted to play

00:21:54.590 --> 00:21:57.860
and it took me a long time
to get back to the dots.

00:21:57.860 --> 00:22:05.750 position:56%
And so, in the meantime I developed
a fairly extensive way of conceiving

00:22:05.750 --> 00:22:12.660
of music and musical structures
that is not notation based.

00:22:12.660 --> 00:22:14.660
I go in the other direction.

00:22:14.660 --> 00:22:18.240
I think somebody like Tunick
started looking at paper and for me

00:22:18.240 --> 00:22:21.220
by the time I looked at the paper,
by the time I knew really what

00:22:21.220 --> 00:22:24.300
that meant, I was making
music for a long time already

00:22:24.300 --> 00:22:27.210
so I can again synthesize
both of those things

00:22:27.210 --> 00:22:29.460
because I've had enough experience
with looking at the paper

00:22:29.460 --> 00:22:34.460
that I know how to make it make
sense but I think if you asked me

00:22:34.460 --> 00:22:40.040
to visualize what one of
my songs is, a lot of it is

00:22:40.040 --> 00:22:42.620
about the placement of
my fingers on the keys.

00:22:42.620 --> 00:22:46.880
I know sort of what the cord
looks like under my hand

00:22:46.880 --> 00:22:51.120
and because I also play without
really looking at my hands,

00:22:51.120 --> 00:22:53.560
it's more that I just
know what it feels like.

00:22:53.560 --> 00:22:56.480
I know what a song is supposed
to feel like under my fingers

00:22:56.480 --> 00:22:59.320
and I don't even know that
that's a visual thing.

00:22:59.320 --> 00:23:04.090
There's a muscular relationship to
my understanding of harmony and how

00:23:04.090 --> 00:23:07.370
that drives through the song
so I think that's really,

00:23:07.370 --> 00:23:10.060
I don't know that that makes
any sense when I say it

00:23:10.060 --> 00:23:13.150
but no one has really asked me to
talk about it before but I think

00:23:13.150 --> 00:23:22.890
if you asked me when I'm trying to
perform a song that I've written

00:23:22.890 --> 00:23:28.140
for example, there are a number
of different sort of cues that are

00:23:28.140 --> 00:23:31.830
in my head so I'm not following
a core in the sense of one

00:23:31.830 --> 00:23:33.330
of those scores over there.

00:23:33.330 --> 00:23:36.820
I'm not following a score but
there is a score in my head

00:23:36.820 --> 00:23:40.690
and it's a bunch of sign posts and
some of those sign posts do consist

00:23:40.690 --> 00:23:47.070 position:56%
of literal written notation and
some of them consist of typed lyrics

00:23:47.070 --> 00:23:49.760
on a page, or hand written lyrics
on a page, some of them consist

00:23:49.760 --> 00:23:52.390
of oh your hands are supposed
to go to this place and some

00:23:52.390 --> 00:23:57.840
of them are just memories about
where I was when I wrote the song.

00:23:57.840 --> 00:24:00.160
There's something about that
that I go oh there's the thing

00:24:00.160 --> 00:24:02.910
and it leads me to that's what
I'm supposed to do at that moment

00:24:02.910 --> 00:24:06.480
because oh, I wrote this when
I was in London or I wrote this

00:24:06.480 --> 00:24:09.850
when I was sitting and the kitchen
was over here and so I know that

00:24:09.850 --> 00:24:12.230
and that's what gets me to there.

00:24:12.230 --> 00:24:14.770
So, there's a whole
crazy thing of memory.

00:24:14.770 --> 00:24:18.720 position:56%
I remember I read a great story in
The New Yorker a couple of years ago

00:24:18.720 --> 00:24:24.650
and it talked about storytellers
in India who they have a story

00:24:24.650 --> 00:24:27.640
that lasts for an entire year
and it's an oral tradition

00:24:27.640 --> 00:24:30.580
so that they are taught as
children, and if they are going

00:24:30.580 --> 00:24:31.910
to become the storyteller
they are taught

00:24:31.910 --> 00:24:34.290
as children how the
story goes and it lasts,

00:24:34.290 --> 00:24:39.130
every night there is a chunk that
could be 20 minutes, an hour long,

00:24:39.130 --> 00:24:43.580
whatever it is but every single
night of the year all 365

00:24:43.580 --> 00:24:47.710
or however many, there is a part
of the story that they have to do

00:24:47.710 --> 00:24:50.350
and they have these
memorized in their heads.

00:24:50.350 --> 00:24:55.600
But they found that once these
people learned to read and write,

00:24:55.600 --> 00:24:59.800
they actually become infinitely
less capable of holding all of that

00:24:59.800 --> 00:25:05.140
in their memory, that you've
developed this incredible memory

00:25:05.140 --> 00:25:08.010
because there's no way
to put it down on paper

00:25:08.010 --> 00:25:11.750
but once you can put it on
paper, once you can do that,

00:25:11.750 --> 00:25:13.900
once you can store
it somewhere else,

00:25:13.900 --> 00:25:18.140
your brain says oh thank goodness
we don't have to do that anymore,

00:25:18.140 --> 00:25:21.540
and it sheds some of it and
so I think part of my ability

00:25:21.540 --> 00:25:25.140
to remember my scores
is because it comes

00:25:25.140 --> 00:25:27.460
from not having notated
them in the first place.

00:25:27.460 --> 00:25:32.000 position:56%
It comes from having a series of
sort of things in my head and I find

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:37.470
that the songs that I do notate
first are the more kind of,

00:25:37.470 --> 00:25:40.830
for lack of a better word, the
more serious classically kind

00:25:40.830 --> 00:25:42.130
of things that I do.

00:25:42.130 --> 00:25:45.330 position:56%
When I have to notate them first, I
find that I have very little ability

00:25:45.330 --> 00:25:48.960 position:56%
to memorize them, it's very hard
for me to reproduce them accurately.

00:25:48.960 --> 00:25:54.660
There's a chunk of Still Hurting
that is a fairly strict invention

00:25:54.660 --> 00:25:59.330
in three parts and it's not just
that I can't really play it all

00:25:59.330 --> 00:26:05.040
that well but after what's now been
15 years, I just know harmonically

00:26:05.040 --> 00:26:07.820
where it's supposed to be but the
specific notes that are supposed

00:26:07.820 --> 00:26:10.800
to happen in there, I'm always
like uh, and I've looked

00:26:10.800 --> 00:26:14.130
at it a thousand times so that
I can do it in performances

00:26:14.130 --> 00:26:16.450
and it just does not penetrate.

00:26:16.450 --> 00:26:18.180 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Every time you perform something,

00:26:18.180 --> 00:26:21.460
this song will always
be in this key?

00:26:21.460 --> 00:26:24.860 position:56%
&gt;&gt; I can change the keys because I
know what the harmonic relationships

00:26:24.860 --> 00:26:26.160
are but-

00:26:26.160 --> 00:26:27.950
&gt;&gt; So the muscle memory can still-

00:26:27.950 --> 00:26:31.360 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I mean I may not play it
as accurately in the key but I mean,

00:26:31.360 --> 00:26:35.480
I know how to, on a technical level
I know how to transpose my stuff.

00:26:35.480 --> 00:26:39.700
There are some things I wouldn't
dare to do but I can make my way

00:26:39.700 --> 00:26:43.150
through it but most
songs belong in the keys,

00:26:43.150 --> 00:26:45.920
in my head most songs believe in
the specific key that I wrote them

00:26:45.920 --> 00:26:47.990
in and I can monkey around.

00:26:47.990 --> 00:26:50.600
I Love Betsy, I wrote
in D, I play it in C

00:26:50.600 --> 00:26:52.830
because I can't really sing
all the high notes if I do it

00:26:52.830 --> 00:26:57.570 position:56%
but it just doesn't belong in C all
that well but I can do it, it's fine

00:26:57.570 --> 00:26:59.670
but it's supposed to be in D.

00:26:59.670 --> 00:27:02.180
&gt;&gt; When you're playing
accompanying yourself,

00:27:02.180 --> 00:27:03.560
is there much improvisation

00:27:03.560 --> 00:27:06.830
or it's pretty much this is
the accompaniment, this is-

00:27:06.830 --> 00:27:08.240
&gt;&gt; No, no, there's a
lot of improvisation.

00:27:08.240 --> 00:27:10.910
I mean some songs, You Don't Know
This Man, there's no improvising

00:27:10.910 --> 00:27:13.810
in that, that is specifically
what it is and a song

00:27:13.810 --> 00:27:18.750
like The Flagmaker is going to be
largely what it is but for a lot

00:27:18.750 --> 00:27:22.740
of my songs there's room
to interpret around it.

00:27:22.740 --> 00:27:25.970
I mean, I am an improvising
pianist, that is part of what I do

00:27:25.970 --> 00:27:29.160
so for me it's more fun if it
doesn't always sort of have to lock

00:27:29.160 --> 00:27:34.080
in exactly like this all the
way and especially for the shows

00:27:34.080 --> 00:27:35.380
that are kind of loose and groovy.

00:27:35.380 --> 00:27:37.810
For a show like Honeymoon in
Vegas you want some of the songs

00:27:37.810 --> 00:27:40.670
to be able to stretch
out and open up.

00:27:40.670 --> 00:27:45.390
It's all within very
specific boundaries.

00:27:45.390 --> 00:27:49.150
I don't reinvent the
songs when I play them,

00:27:49.150 --> 00:27:52.500 position:56%
it's just these two bars it could be
this thing or it could be this thing

00:27:52.500 --> 00:27:55.170
but the basic feel
and harmonic structure

00:27:55.170 --> 00:27:56.470
of it is going to be the same.

00:27:56.470 --> 00:28:00.040
There's just filigree that
can change from time to time.

00:28:00.040 --> 00:28:03.130
And again, I think that's
more a pop music thing.

00:28:03.130 --> 00:28:05.030
It's basically just riffing.

00:28:05.030 --> 00:28:08.810
I feel free to make those
changes within some of the songs

00:28:08.810 --> 00:28:10.110
because it's part of the fun

00:28:10.110 --> 00:28:11.840
of performing them is
to let them breathe.

00:28:11.840 --> 00:28:18.110
&gt;&gt; Will you sit in your living room
and just play Isn't it Romantic or-

00:28:18.110 --> 00:28:19.960
&gt;&gt; Sure, all the time.

00:28:19.960 --> 00:28:25.100
Yeah, especially with, it was part
