00:36:46.440 --> 00:36:48.910
You will hear probably
my stomach rumbling.

00:36:48.910 --> 00:36:53.830
That's what I get for not eating
breakfast before my interview.

00:36:53.830 --> 00:36:55.710
&gt;&gt; I'm sorry, sorry.

00:36:55.710 --> 00:37:02.500
When I read through your music,
I'm just constantly sort of in awe

00:37:02.500 --> 00:37:11.460
of your vamps and accompaniments
and the inventiveness of them

00:37:11.460 --> 00:37:15.450
and partly also the
frequency of them.

00:37:15.450 --> 00:37:19.320
Not every song from
other songwriters seem

00:37:19.320 --> 00:37:24.110
to so frequently sort of
use those kinds of vamps.

00:37:24.110 --> 00:37:27.920
They tend to seem more
chordal to me and yours,

00:37:27.920 --> 00:37:30.860
there's always something
interesting going on underneath

00:37:30.860 --> 00:37:34.160
and I don't know what you
can comment on about that.

00:37:34.160 --> 00:37:37.910
&gt;&gt; I'm a groove guy
ultimately and so groove is sort

00:37:37.910 --> 00:37:41.870
of how the songs are
built and groove you know,

00:37:41.870 --> 00:37:44.680
I wouldn't use the same groove
for two different songs so even

00:37:44.680 --> 00:37:47.210
if the tempos are pretty much
exactly the same and even

00:37:47.210 --> 00:37:49.100
if the fields are pretty
much exactly the same,

00:37:49.100 --> 00:37:52.900
something in that groove has to
change in order for me to write.

00:37:52.900 --> 00:37:55.980
I really do write rhythmically
I think,

00:37:55.980 --> 00:38:02.430
even the melodies I write are
built on a rhythmic basis.

00:38:02.430 --> 00:38:05.930
There is an idea that a thing
goes for a certain period of time

00:38:05.930 --> 00:38:09.820
and that the, I think it's why
I'm a lyricist is because I think

00:38:09.820 --> 00:38:16.740
of speech in a very rhythmic
way and so once there's groove,

00:38:16.740 --> 00:38:20.750
sort of anything can happen over it
but until I find that groove I sort

00:38:20.750 --> 00:38:22.780
of don't know what the
song is supposed to be

00:38:22.780 --> 00:38:26.030 position:56%
and I have written a couple of songs
where I just did have sort of chords

00:38:26.030 --> 00:38:27.820
in advance and didn't
have a real groove

00:38:27.820 --> 00:38:34.940
and those songs always feel kind
of uncomfortable fungible to me.

00:38:34.940 --> 00:38:39.200 position:56%
Well, if it could be anything then
I guess it's just anything you know,

00:38:39.200 --> 00:38:42.010
Stars in The Moon, when
Betty Buckley does it

00:38:42.010 --> 00:38:44.640 position:56%
with her band it's a whole different
groove that she has but Stars

00:38:44.640 --> 00:38:49.370
in the Moon itself is specifically
that groove that I wrote into it

00:38:49.370 --> 00:38:52.870 position:56%
and I wouldn't have known how to
write the song without that pattern.

00:38:52.870 --> 00:38:55.540
That is sort of what
drives the rest of it.

00:38:55.540 --> 00:39:01.840 position:56%
&gt;&gt; It may interest you, we have
several collections where it's clear

00:39:01.840 --> 00:39:04.660
that the rhythm sort
of does come first.

00:39:04.660 --> 00:39:09.560
In the Rodgers collection, he
has the typed lyric sheet for one

00:39:09.560 --> 00:39:13.470
of the songs from Cinderella
and he puts in bar marks

00:39:13.470 --> 00:39:17.630
and then writes the rhythms
and then finds the melody.

00:39:17.630 --> 00:39:21.640
&gt;&gt; Yeah because with Hammerstein,
he always wrote the lyrics first

00:39:21.640 --> 00:39:23.430
and then put the melodies
afterwards so yeah,

00:39:23.430 --> 00:39:27.170
you can see where that would
make exactly sense there

00:39:27.170 --> 00:39:35.600 position:56%
and I think I do things like that
up here a lot all the time but yeah,

00:39:35.600 --> 00:39:40.100
especially with popular based music
there is always a sense of meter,

00:39:40.100 --> 00:39:42.930
that meter is kind of
what drives the thing.

00:39:42.930 --> 00:39:45.340
I have occasionally tried to
figure out how I can write things

00:39:45.340 --> 00:39:48.670
that are meter-less, what does
that mean and just what is it,

00:39:48.670 --> 00:39:51.800
that would be an interesting
idea for me to try,

00:39:51.800 --> 00:39:55.260
what is something that's
non-metered, entirely non-metered?

00:39:55.260 --> 00:40:00.730
I find it really kind of,
even when I hear it back even

00:40:00.730 --> 00:40:03.150
when I've written this thing
that the audience is not supposed

00:40:03.150 --> 00:40:06.200
to perceive any kind of meter
in, I still sort of feel like no,

00:40:06.200 --> 00:40:07.870
I still hear it, I
still know exactly sort

00:40:07.870 --> 00:40:09.840
of where events are
supposed to happen

00:40:09.840 --> 00:40:12.100
in a real metric sense of the word.

00:40:12.100 --> 00:40:15.750
&gt;&gt; It's funny, in Bridges
of Madison County,

00:40:15.750 --> 00:40:19.740
I was sort of following the
recording with vocal selections

00:40:19.740 --> 00:40:24.330
and all of a sudden I
realized I think seven or eight

00:40:24.330 --> 00:40:28.140
of the songs were either in three
four or in some triple meter.

00:40:28.140 --> 00:40:29.440
Was that intentional?

00:40:29.440 --> 00:40:30.740
Was that more romantic?

00:40:30.740 --> 00:40:33.030
&gt;&gt; It wasn't no, I think that's
just how I played the guitar.

00:40:33.030 --> 00:40:35.160 position:56%
There was a certain strumming rhythm

00:40:35.160 --> 00:40:37.410
that just sort of led
me to that thing.

00:40:37.410 --> 00:40:41.560
No, not just, I mean they're all
in twelve eight or some version

00:40:41.560 --> 00:40:43.920
of twelve eight but I mean
essentially it's the same

00:40:43.920 --> 00:40:45.220
metronome marking.

00:40:45.220 --> 00:40:47.110
It was really clear this
is how I play the guitar.

00:40:47.110 --> 00:40:48.430
&gt;&gt; Did that surprise
you or were you-

00:40:48.430 --> 00:40:50.150
&gt;&gt; It did, I really
thought I wasn't doing that.

00:40:50.150 --> 00:40:51.620
I really thought oh
this is so clever,

00:40:51.620 --> 00:40:53.060
I'm coming up with all
these different things

00:40:53.060 --> 00:40:55.650
and then I just overheard
the music director saying

00:40:55.650 --> 00:40:58.840 position:56%
to the guitarist one day oh no, it's
the exact same metronome marking,

00:40:58.840 --> 00:41:01.780 position:56%
it's the same feel as the song
right before it and I was like what?

00:41:01.780 --> 00:41:06.410
And he said no, no,
they're exactly the same.

00:41:06.410 --> 00:41:08.380
But you know, and then when
I conducted the show I was

00:41:08.380 --> 00:41:09.680
like no, he's absolutely right.

00:41:09.680 --> 00:41:14.550
It was Look At Me goes
into World Inside a Frame

00:41:14.550 --> 00:41:19.300 position:56%
and they are exactly da, da, da
just exactly right in the same place

00:41:19.300 --> 00:41:21.480
but it works, it's
what I wanted to say.

00:41:21.480 --> 00:41:25.930
&gt;&gt; When you're sort of planning a
score, do you think of here's an

00:41:25.930 --> 00:41:29.890
up tempo, it needs to be
followed by a ballad, here's-

00:41:29.890 --> 00:41:33.730
&gt;&gt; Well yeah, you know,
because you're

00:41:33.730 --> 00:41:36.620
on that particular ride you can
feel when you're just sort of stuck

00:41:36.620 --> 00:41:38.420
at the traffic light for
too long and you can feel

00:41:38.420 --> 00:41:41.700
when you've been going too fast
and you've got to pull it back.

00:41:41.700 --> 00:41:45.460
You know, the energy of
storytelling I think is a big part

00:41:45.460 --> 00:41:46.930
of what composers do.

00:41:46.930 --> 00:41:48.590
I think if you're going
to write a musical,

00:41:48.590 --> 00:41:50.600
mostly what you're doing
is controlling the energy

00:41:50.600 --> 00:41:53.880
of the storytelling,
controlling the pace of it and so

00:41:53.880 --> 00:41:57.210
to me it's very important
to stay on top

00:41:57.210 --> 00:42:00.210
of are we going at the right speed?

00:42:00.210 --> 00:42:04.010
Is the information being
given out at the right speed

00:42:04.010 --> 00:42:07.060
and is the energy sort of the right
energy that we need at this moment

00:42:07.060 --> 00:42:08.820
or have we been up for too long?

00:42:08.820 --> 00:42:12.030
Most musicals, you hit the second
act and it's just an endless pile

00:42:12.030 --> 00:42:16.400
of ballads which drives me bananas
and so I try never to get caught

00:42:16.400 --> 00:42:21.170
in that trap but there's a reason
why, because as all the sort of,

00:42:21.170 --> 00:42:23.900 position:56%
as you're getting to the [inaudible]
all of the complications are sort

00:42:23.900 --> 00:42:26.750 position:56%
of coming and so everybody is
getting very reflective and very sad

00:42:26.750 --> 00:42:30.340
and so that's why the second act
tends to be burdened by reprises

00:42:30.340 --> 00:42:33.060
and ballads but I try to
keep that from happening.

00:42:33.060 --> 00:42:37.920
&gt;&gt; Do you find the audience tells
you things when you're out of town

00:42:37.920 --> 00:42:41.900
or in previews, you get the
sense that how they are?

00:42:41.900 --> 00:42:44.870
&gt;&gt; They do but it's not so
much about that as it really is

00:42:44.870 --> 00:42:46.810
about me sitting in
the audience being able

00:42:46.810 --> 00:42:48.870 position:56%
to experience it through their eyes.

00:42:48.870 --> 00:42:52.400
It's not like I have some psychic
ability to feel that an audience,

00:42:52.400 --> 00:42:54.330
you can feel when they're
really with you and you can feel

00:42:54.330 --> 00:42:57.550
when they're not but that
changes from day to day honestly.

00:42:57.550 --> 00:42:59.780
Even if a show works
perfectly there's some days

00:42:59.780 --> 00:43:02.050
where the audience is really with
it and some days when they're not

00:43:02.050 --> 00:43:04.880 position:56%
so I try not to go too much on like,

00:43:04.880 --> 00:43:08.820
oh they didn't applaud too much
tonight because you can go crazy.

00:43:08.820 --> 00:43:16.380
But there is a sense of there is
a certain kind of state you have

00:43:16.380 --> 00:43:20.460
to get into, a state of total
focus when you're watching a show

00:43:20.460 --> 00:43:23.800
which is hard to do if you're the
writer because you can get trapped

00:43:23.800 --> 00:43:27.410
by oh, I just heard the bassoon
play an E flat or you know,

00:43:27.410 --> 00:43:30.420
why is that light going
or even just why is

00:43:30.420 --> 00:43:32.850
that person unwrapping
a candy over here?

00:43:32.850 --> 00:43:36.700
But that state of total focus of
I am the ideal audience member

00:43:36.700 --> 00:43:40.310
for this piece right now, how am
I receiving it, how is it coming

00:43:40.310 --> 00:43:46.320
at me, and so it takes a
lot and I think with all

00:43:46.320 --> 00:43:51.180 position:56%
of our endless distractions these
days it's harder for me than it used

00:43:51.180 --> 00:43:56.010
to be to get into that state of
total focus but when you're in it,

00:43:56.010 --> 00:44:00.090
that really is what tells
me the most about a show.

00:44:00.090 --> 00:44:02.470
There are always some little
niggling thing in the back

00:44:02.470 --> 00:44:05.580
of your head that says boy, this
is going on a little too long

00:44:05.580 --> 00:44:09.340
and you can have that feeling
for like, four performances

00:44:09.340 --> 00:44:11.710
and never really articulate it.

00:44:11.710 --> 00:44:13.930
It just sort of comes
and then you know,

00:44:13.930 --> 00:44:16.100
the director will say something
like something's just not right

00:44:16.100 --> 00:44:19.610
about the top and you'll find
yourself saying actually,

00:44:19.610 --> 00:44:20.910
it's too long.

00:44:20.910 --> 00:44:23.340
The number is too long,
let me cut this chunk of it

00:44:23.340 --> 00:44:27.830
but it will have taken that many
times through it for that thought

00:44:27.830 --> 00:44:31.730
to make its way all the way from
the back of my brain into my mouth

00:44:31.730 --> 00:44:33.620
and I find that happens a lot.

00:44:33.620 --> 00:44:34.930
I find there are a lot of places

00:44:34.930 --> 00:44:39.760 position:56%
where the pacing just takes me a
couple of days to say you know what,

00:44:39.760 --> 00:44:46.950
I resist cuts for a long time
not because I'm so precious

00:44:46.950 --> 00:44:49.170
about the work but
because I generally feel

00:44:49.170 --> 00:44:54.110
like if I've conceived it right,
it shouldn't be about cutting it.

00:44:54.110 --> 00:44:56.170
There's something that
I did right about this

00:44:56.170 --> 00:44:57.940
so let's not make the wrong choice.

00:44:57.940 --> 00:45:00.200
Cutting is easy, cutting
is an easy fix.

00:45:00.200 --> 00:45:06.620
Oh, we'll just take this out but
there is a fix that we can find.

00:45:06.620 --> 00:45:09.440
Let's make sure it's the right one
and often it is about cutting it

00:45:09.440 --> 00:45:11.320
but it may not be about
cutting what everyone things,

00:45:11.320 --> 00:45:15.000
it's about cutting what happened
two minutes earlier it's that.

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:17.960
So I try to stay very
present and alert for it.

00:45:17.960 --> 00:45:21.220
It's hard, it's hard, it's a
hard thing to do but I find

00:45:21.220 --> 00:45:23.920
that I can't do it unless there's
a whole audience around me.

00:45:23.920 --> 00:45:29.310
&gt;&gt; I'm curious about the
arranging and orchestrating.

00:45:29.310 --> 00:45:33.500 position:56%
Were you trained in that or was that
something from Eastman or you just-

00:45:33.500 --> 00:45:37.550
&gt;&gt; When I was in high school and
we would do talent shows and things

00:45:37.550 --> 00:45:39.900
like that, and if I wanted horn
sections because I always did

00:45:39.900 --> 00:45:45.850
because I was a kid who wanted big
bands around me, I had to you know,

00:45:45.850 --> 00:45:50.380
you can read about it in books but
mainly you're just doing it by ear.

00:45:50.380 --> 00:45:53.630
Stuff like horn charts,
jazz band kind of things,

00:45:53.630 --> 00:45:57.130
you know I would play in jazz
bands and stuff like that

00:45:57.130 --> 00:46:03.180 position:56%
so I had a certain amount of fluency
with that already but so I did some

00:46:03.180 --> 00:46:05.830 position:56%
of it in high school and knew enough
to sort of get through a chart.

00:46:05.830 --> 00:46:08.090
They weren't particularly good
charts but I could do that.

00:46:08.090 --> 00:46:09.390
I did study it at Eastman.

00:46:09.390 --> 00:46:13.110
I was only at Eastman for two
years but I studied orchestration

00:46:13.110 --> 00:46:16.100
as you do as a composition major
so I studied that and I played

00:46:16.100 --> 00:46:19.450
in the orchestras and I got all
of that but I would really say

00:46:19.450 --> 00:46:23.740
that the most education I got was

00:46:23.740 --> 00:46:26.570
from watching Sebesky
orchestrate Parade.

00:46:26.570 --> 00:46:31.220
Those charts would come in and I
would see how he was taking my work

00:46:31.220 --> 00:46:34.530
and orchestrating it,
that the trust that he had

00:46:34.530 --> 00:46:36.700
in some things I would
do as a pianist

00:46:36.700 --> 00:46:40.780
and then the way he would ignore
certain things I did as a pianist

00:46:40.780 --> 00:46:42.480
in terms of how he blew that up

00:46:42.480 --> 00:46:47.710
so I think I really became a
vastly better orchestrator the day

00:46:47.710 --> 00:46:50.470
that Sebesky started orchestrating
my work for me and some

00:46:50.470 --> 00:46:53.610
of that had started earlier because
Tunick had done Petrified Prince,

00:46:53.610 --> 00:46:54.910
which I was musical director for.

00:46:54.910 --> 00:46:57.730
It was the Michael John LaChiusa
show and again, I had played it

00:46:57.730 --> 00:47:00.390
and a lot of the piano arrangements
were my piano arrangements

00:47:00.390 --> 00:47:03.570
and then watching Tunick sort of
take those on but we were working

00:47:03.570 --> 00:47:05.760
with a very small orchestra
in that show.

00:47:05.760 --> 00:47:10.290
It was only I think seven pieces
and so there were some lessons

00:47:10.290 --> 00:47:14.080
that Jonathan taught me there
that I didn't really put together

00:47:14.080 --> 00:47:18.560 position:56%
for 15 years when I finally was able
to say oh, I see now why he did it

00:47:18.560 --> 00:47:20.830
that way, I see what
he was doing back them.

00:47:20.830 --> 00:47:26.720
But in terms of the immediate like,
I can tell you the immediate impact

00:47:26.720 --> 00:47:29.650
that it had watching Sebesky's
charts come in for Parade.

00:47:29.650 --> 00:47:34.360
&gt;&gt; I did an interview with Tunick
and I am naïve when it comes

00:47:34.360 --> 00:47:37.230
to orchestration so although
I find it fascinating,

00:47:37.230 --> 00:47:39.770
and one of the things
that he sort of expounded

00:47:39.770 --> 00:47:45.310
on that sparked me was the
importance of part writing

00:47:45.310 --> 00:47:52.170
and as I understood him, he thinks
it's important as much as possible

00:47:52.170 --> 00:47:55.370
that every instrument is playing a
piece of music, they're not filling

00:47:55.370 --> 00:47:57.320
in a chord or something like that

00:47:57.320 --> 00:48:00.580
because then they'll
play more musically and-

00:48:00.580 --> 00:48:02.120
&gt;&gt; Yeah and I think I got that.

00:48:02.120 --> 00:48:04.580
I think that I got intuitively
because I was a chorale singer

00:48:04.580 --> 00:48:06.770
and I did a lot of
chorale arranging.

00:48:06.770 --> 00:48:09.050
Vocal arranging was the thing I did
most of when I was in high school

00:48:09.050 --> 00:48:11.620
because we had a jazz
vocal group that I was part

00:48:11.620 --> 00:48:14.540
of that I had one teacher who was
just, she was nuts for Lambert,

00:48:14.540 --> 00:48:16.800
Hendricks &amp; Ross and she was
nuts for the Manhattan Transfer,

00:48:16.800 --> 00:48:19.950
and so we would try and do all
of that stuff so I spent a lot

00:48:19.950 --> 00:48:23.230
of time doing vocal arranging
and so because of that,

00:48:23.230 --> 00:48:26.050
I think I intuitively knew
what Tunick was saying

00:48:26.050 --> 00:48:29.040
which was you don't want to
just tell the altos to just sort

00:48:29.040 --> 00:48:32.320
of hit an A in the middle of this
and then be tacit for the rest.

00:48:32.320 --> 00:48:34.660
You want to figure out how
to get them to it musically

00:48:34.660 --> 00:48:38.810
and so I think I try and do that as
an orchestrator also but you know,

00:48:38.810 --> 00:48:44.320
I have a, I don't posit myself as
the world's greatest orchestrator.

00:48:44.320 --> 00:48:46.890
I mean, I'm not a master
of it, I really do it

00:48:46.890 --> 00:48:49.230
and I think I do it
well for my own stuff

00:48:49.230 --> 00:48:53.610
and I have a very specific sound
as an orchestrator but I don't feel

00:48:53.610 --> 00:48:59.320
like I really even now got an
entire handle on all of the tools

00:48:59.320 --> 00:49:00.620
of an orchestrators trade.

00:49:00.620 --> 00:49:03.130
I feel like I'm still sort of
masquerading as an orchestrator.

00:49:03.130 --> 00:49:06.700 position:56%
You know, there are people who spend
their lives doing it and know a lot

00:49:06.700 --> 00:49:09.210
about color and a lot about texture

00:49:09.210 --> 00:49:12.390
that I am really feeling
my way in the dark for.

00:49:12.390 --> 00:49:14.850
&gt;&gt; When you're composing it
from the beginning do you ever

00:49:14.850 --> 00:49:16.150
think instrumentally?

00:49:16.150 --> 00:49:18.190
&gt;&gt; Oh always I mean, you know,

00:49:18.190 --> 00:49:19.950
and sometimes instrumentally
means I'm thinking

00:49:19.950 --> 00:49:23.270
about how the piano functions
in the piece but yeah no, no,

00:49:23.270 --> 00:49:25.680
I've always got a pretty
clear sense but again,

00:49:25.680 --> 00:49:29.400
because a lot of my stuff is kind
of rock based and groove based,

00:49:29.400 --> 00:49:31.860
I'm mainly thinking about how
the rhythm section functions

00:49:31.860 --> 00:49:33.590
and what the drums are
doing and what the,

00:49:33.590 --> 00:49:35.650
I've got that for any
song I've written.

00:49:35.650 --> 00:49:38.900
I know what that is supposed
to be and then you know,

00:49:38.900 --> 00:49:41.730
for things like Parade or
Bridges of Madison County

00:49:41.730 --> 00:49:45.800 position:56%
which have a wider palate of colors,
I've generally got that in my head

00:49:45.800 --> 00:49:50.750
as I'm writing as well but then
until you get out the paper

00:49:50.750 --> 00:49:52.050
and start filling it out-

00:49:52.050 --> 00:49:53.520
&gt;&gt; How different was
it doing Trumpet

00:49:53.520 --> 00:49:57.040
of the Swan or something that's-

00:49:57.040 --> 00:49:58.340
&gt;&gt; Trumpet of the Swan you know,

00:49:58.340 --> 00:50:04.420 position:56%
I had a very specific orchestral
template in mind and when Sam Davis,

00:50:04.420 --> 00:50:06.670 position:56%
who did the orchestrations, I just
thought there was no way I was going

00:50:06.670 --> 00:50:08.480
to have time to do them, but so

00:50:08.480 --> 00:50:11.210
when Sam did them I sent
him before he started,

00:50:11.210 --> 00:50:15.610
I said these are the three pieces
that you need to know about

00:50:15.610 --> 00:50:18.900
and I think one of
them was Petrushka,

00:50:18.900 --> 00:50:22.480
one of them was Randall
Thompson's Second Symphony,

00:50:22.480 --> 00:50:25.730
which is maybe the most obscure
reference I could possibly throw

00:50:25.730 --> 00:50:27.560
out but I always loved it.

00:50:27.560 --> 00:50:30.710 position:56%
Randall Thompson I knew as a chorale
writer which is the way most kids

00:50:30.710 --> 00:50:33.450 position:56%
in high school know him because they
sing the Alleluia or whatever it was

00:50:33.450 --> 00:50:35.890 position:56%
and so I remember going to
Finkelstein Library when I was a kid

00:50:35.890 --> 00:50:38.130
and saying what else do you
have of Randall Thompson

00:50:38.130 --> 00:50:40.990
and there was a recording Bernstein
did of this Second Symphony,

00:50:40.990 --> 00:50:45.610
which was sort of as close as he
ever got to a hit symphonically

00:50:45.610 --> 00:50:48.480
and so I just remember
hearing it in high school

00:50:48.480 --> 00:50:50.110
and just thinking it was the
greatest piece in the world.

00:50:50.110 --> 00:50:54.300
And so, I think it was Petrushka,
the Thompson Second Symphony,

00:50:54.300 --> 00:50:59.780
and Korngold's score for Robin Hood
and so I sent those three things

00:50:59.780 --> 00:51:02.710
to Sam and I said these are the
basic colors we're dealing with

00:51:02.710 --> 00:51:06.520
and there are really specific
things in Trumpet of the Swan

00:51:06.520 --> 00:51:09.290
where clearly I'm just stealing
from one of those three pieces

00:51:09.290 --> 00:51:12.850
and that's just sort
of what's on the table.

00:51:12.850 --> 00:51:17.200
But you know, what I sent
to Sam was a short score,

00:51:17.200 --> 00:51:21.950
it was largely piano part with
probably one or two other stabs

00:51:21.950 --> 00:51:25.150
of things and then he would send
me an orchestration which I would

00:51:25.150 --> 00:51:30.950
as often as not sort of completely
throw up in the air and re-do

00:51:30.950 --> 00:51:34.210
but the gestures were pretty clear

00:51:34.210 --> 00:51:35.730
and you could see them
in my short score.

00:51:35.730 --> 00:51:39.230
I'd write woodwinds play this
chord and this thing is supposed

00:51:39.230 --> 00:51:43.270 position:56%
to be French horns playing it, it's
all pretty well delineated in there.

00:51:43.270 --> 00:51:48.640
&gt;&gt; A friend of mine played bass
in Last Five Years in a production

00:51:48.640 --> 00:51:51.980
and he said it was
the most satisfying-

00:51:51.980 --> 00:51:55.310
&gt;&gt; For a bass player especially
yeah, I should hope so.

00:51:55.310 --> 00:51:58.460
You know, that was really again,

00:51:58.460 --> 00:52:02.240
each of the shows has a really
distinct sound by design.

00:52:02.240 --> 00:52:07.140
I want the shows to sort of
build a world within themselves

00:52:07.140 --> 00:52:12.600
so that any show, you can't put any
of those songs into any other show.

00:52:12.600 --> 00:52:16.100
They sort of belong where they are
but more specifically than that,

00:52:16.100 --> 00:52:19.190
the instrumentation that
surrounds them is very specific

00:52:19.190 --> 00:52:20.580
to how I'm writing them so I knew

00:52:20.580 --> 00:52:23.270
with the Last Five Years not only
was it not going to have a drummer

00:52:23.270 --> 00:52:29.370
in it but I also knew that what I
wanted was specifically there's a

00:52:29.370 --> 00:52:31.930
Joni Mitchell album, there's Hejira

00:52:31.930 --> 00:52:33.860
and there's Don Juan's
Reckless Daughter,

00:52:33.860 --> 00:52:37.350
both of which she explores the
idea of not using a drummer

00:52:37.350 --> 00:52:40.200
but letting the fretless
bass was Jaco Pastorius,

00:52:40.200 --> 00:52:46.250
letting that be the kind of
melodic glue that holds it together

00:52:46.250 --> 00:52:49.190
and the guitars are
really just hard rhythm,

00:52:49.190 --> 00:52:51.110
