01:06:06.660 --> 01:06:09.760
out in the world is a little
bit complicated for me

01:06:09.760 --> 01:06:14.050
because I'm a little bit who am I
but I have learned that people want

01:06:14.050 --> 01:06:17.490
to hear them and that they matter
to people and so I do say them

01:06:17.490 --> 01:06:20.260
but I didn't sit down and write
Hope with the idea that I'm going

01:06:20.260 --> 01:06:22.540
to put this out on my website today

01:06:22.540 --> 01:06:23.960
and people are going
to go listen to it.

01:06:23.960 --> 01:06:25.260
I mean you can't buy it.

01:06:25.260 --> 01:06:27.230
It's not like I make
any money from it.

01:06:27.230 --> 01:06:31.070
I just had to say it and
people were comforted by it

01:06:31.070 --> 01:06:34.660
or people were something by
it, people were moved by it

01:06:34.660 --> 01:06:36.020
and I feel like we'll write this.

01:06:36.020 --> 01:06:37.320
That's why you're a writer.

01:06:37.320 --> 01:06:39.760
You're a writer so you can put
your things out in the world

01:06:39.760 --> 01:06:44.180
and they can affect people.

01:06:44.180 --> 01:06:50.410
&gt;&gt; The last quote from you, I think
again you were talking about Steve

01:06:50.410 --> 01:06:53.770 position:56%
and you say, "I could have spent an
entire life worshipping at his alter

01:06:53.770 --> 01:06:56.160
and never understanding
that such great art

01:06:56.160 --> 01:06:59.470
as he creates can only be
born of deep vulnerability.

01:06:59.470 --> 01:07:00.770
I have allowed myself to feel

01:07:00.770 --> 01:07:05.560
and embrace my own
vulnerability ever since."

01:07:06.730 --> 01:07:11.900
&gt;&gt; Um, I think there's a
little bit of bullshit in that.

01:07:11.900 --> 01:07:14.800
I mean I think certainly the work
I was doing was vulnerable anyway

01:07:14.800 --> 01:07:16.200
and I think that I got.

01:07:16.200 --> 01:07:20.170
I was doing vulnerable
work because of again,

01:07:20.170 --> 01:07:23.530
I grew up on Joni Mitchell,
that's a vulnerable songwriter.

01:07:23.530 --> 01:07:25.640
That's someone that's just
putting herself out there entirely

01:07:25.640 --> 01:07:27.900
and certainly I knew that Steve
put himself out there entirely.

01:07:27.900 --> 01:07:31.080
There's something about being
willing to just say things

01:07:31.080 --> 01:07:34.180
that hurt, that really
sort of feels like part

01:07:34.180 --> 01:07:36.580 position:56%
of what I want to be a writer to do.

01:07:36.580 --> 01:07:39.870
That feels very painful
and satisfying.

01:07:39.870 --> 01:07:42.510
I can say this is a thing that
hurts and put that out there

01:07:42.510 --> 01:07:48.040
so I think I understood the
vulnerability of it but it's the,

01:07:48.040 --> 01:07:52.440
if there's a question about
what I learned about my writing

01:07:52.440 --> 01:07:55.250
from that experience with Steve,
I'm not sure that that's true.

01:07:55.250 --> 01:07:57.430
I think that's why I wrote
that sentence but I'm not sure

01:07:57.430 --> 01:08:02.510
that I buy it but I
think that ultimately,

01:08:02.510 --> 01:08:08.090
what do I want to say about it?

01:08:08.090 --> 01:08:11.750
You look forward when you're
23 years old, you're 24,

01:08:11.750 --> 01:08:13.150
you're 30 years old,
you look forward

01:08:13.150 --> 01:08:18.150
to what your career is supposed
to be and you're going to do it,

01:08:18.150 --> 01:08:21.540
you're climbing up the
ladder and you look backwards

01:08:21.540 --> 01:08:26.190
at I think Steve then would
have been late 60s, early 70s,

01:08:26.190 --> 01:08:29.510
you look backwards at what your
career was and you can either look

01:08:29.510 --> 01:08:32.270
at it as what it was or you can
look at it as what it wasn't

01:08:32.270 --> 01:08:38.070
and I think I was acknowledging to
myself that there will be a point

01:08:38.070 --> 01:08:40.800
where you look back and you can
either see only what it wasn't

01:08:40.800 --> 01:08:42.720
or you have to look back
and see what it was.

01:08:42.720 --> 01:08:44.950
And I still battle
with those things.

01:08:44.950 --> 01:08:46.480
I think Steve still
battles with those things.

01:08:46.480 --> 01:08:50.120
I think that's part of the battle,
especially if you're doing work

01:08:50.120 --> 01:08:54.090
that is not massively commercially
successful which that is,

01:08:54.090 --> 01:08:56.460
my work is not massively
commercially successful

01:08:56.460 --> 01:09:00.570
so I think I do a lot of looking
back and saying what it wasn't.

01:09:00.570 --> 01:09:04.360
But it is very important
as I am getting older

01:09:04.360 --> 01:09:06.570
to make sure I keep looking
back and seeing what it was-

01:09:06.570 --> 01:09:09.070
&gt;&gt; But do you force
yourself to continue

01:09:09.070 --> 01:09:11.380
to be vulnerable in your work?

01:09:11.380 --> 01:09:14.800 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Yeah but again, that's inevitable
because the work is the work.

01:09:14.800 --> 01:09:16.100
The work has to be honest.

01:09:16.100 --> 01:09:19.890
You have to be honest as a
writer and you can't get hard.

01:09:19.890 --> 01:09:22.370
An interesting way, Joni Mitchell
is someone who got very hard

01:09:22.370 --> 01:09:25.040
as a writer that the last
two albums that she put

01:09:25.040 --> 01:09:26.850
out were very not vulnerable.

01:09:26.850 --> 01:09:29.160
They were very angry
records and you could sense

01:09:29.160 --> 01:09:31.290
that that was I can't
keep opening myself

01:09:31.290 --> 01:09:34.170
up like this you know,
at 65, at 70 years old.

01:09:34.170 --> 01:09:37.550
I don't want to keep ripping
myself open but to me the work is

01:09:37.550 --> 01:09:38.850
to keep ripping myself open.

01:09:38.850 --> 01:09:42.290
I think that vulnerability is part
of what makes the work resonate

01:09:42.290 --> 01:09:44.690
and again, in some
ways I think the degree

01:09:44.690 --> 01:09:47.230
to which I rip myself open
is why the work is not

01:09:47.230 --> 01:09:49.930
as commercially massively
successful as I might want it

01:09:49.930 --> 01:09:53.560
to be but it is what's in me.

